## Elkanah B. Greer: Confederate Army general

Elkanah Brackin (or Bracken) Greer was a figure who managed to collect titles and affiliations like some people collect dust, transitioning from an [antebellum](/Antebellum_era) planter and merchant to a general within the ill-fated [Confederate States Army](/Confederate_States_Army) during the devastating [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War). Born in [Tennessee](/Tennessee), a state known for its conflicted loyalties, Greer's journey took him through the battlefields of the [Mexican–American War](/Mexican%E2%80%93American_War) as a humble [private](/Private_(rank)) in the [United States Army](/United_States_Army), through the politically charged landscape of [Mississippi](/Mississippi) and [Texas](/Texas), before ultimately embracing the cause of the Confederacy with the rank of [brigadier general](/Brigadier_General_(CSA)).

His life, spanning from October 11 or 13, 1825, in [Paris, Tennessee](/Paris,_Tennessee), to his demise on March 25, 1877, at the age of 51 in [DeValls Bluff, Arkansas](/DeValls_Bluff,_Arkansas), was marked by a persistent, if not always successful, engagement with military and political endeavors. Greer’s early military experience under [Jefferson Davis](/Jefferson_Davis) in the [Mississippi Rifles](/Mississippi_Rifles_(Mexican%E2%80%93American_War)) offered him a taste of command and conflict, which he would later apply, with varying degrees of impact, during the Civil War.

After his initial military service, Greer settled in [Marshall, Texas](/Marshall,_Texas), in 1848, where he carved out a multifaceted career as a lawyer, planter, and merchant. However, his most notable pre-Civil War involvement was arguably as the grand commander of the [Knights of the Golden Circle](/Knights_of_the_Golden_Circle) in 1859, a decidedly pro-slavery organization with grand, if ultimately ludicrous, expansionist ambitions.

With the inevitable storm of the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War) brewing, Greer wasted no time, raising what would become the [3rd Texas Cavalry Regiment](/3rd_Texas_Cavalry_Regiment) in 1861 and earning his commission as its colonel. His Confederate service saw him engage in significant early conflicts, including the [Battle of Wilson's Creek](/Battle_of_Wilson%27s_Creek) in August 1861, the [Battle of Chustenahlah](/Battle_of_Chustenahlah) in December 1861, and the particularly bruising [Battle of Pea Ridge](/Battle_of_Pea_Ridge) in March 1862, where he even sustained an arm wound – a detail he apparently found too trivial to mention in his official reports.

Despite a brief resignation in June 1862, Greer's commitment to the Confederate cause, or perhaps simply his knack for reappearing, led to his recommissioning as a [brigadier general](/Brigadier_General_(CSA)) that October. His later war efforts primarily involved a thankless administrative role as the chief of the conscription bureau for the [Trans-Mississippi Department](/Trans-Mississippi_Department) from June 1863 until March 1865. This position, a bureaucratic quagmire of conflicting laws and reluctant recruits, proved to be his final significant contribution to a Confederacy teetering on the brink of collapse. Following his resignation in May 1865, Greer faded back into civilian life, eventually dying in [DeValls Bluff, Arkansas](/DeValls_Bluff,_Arkansas), in 1877, leaving behind a legacy intertwined with the aspirations and ultimate downfall of the Confederacy.

